US 10-Year Treasury yield on February 10, 2022 was 2.03%, only 0.22% below 2.25%. Given the anticipated interest rate hike in March, there is a high probability of exceeding 2.25% before July 1, 2022. I will use current crowd forecast of 57% as my starting base.

Updating in response to the yield briefly exceeding 2% for the first time since 2019 during the past few days–and it’s only mid-February. Extrapolating 3-month and 6-month avg. trends puts the yield dangerously near (or slightly above!) 2.25% by July. Considering the higher likelihood that current trends continue and that some additional fluctuations will occur above and below the longer-term trends, it now seems significantly more likely than not that we will see the 2.25% threshold be exceeded by at least a small amount and for a short time.

Have learned an important piece of information about this challenge: the volatility of the 10 year rate has increased markedly over time - even when logged! I didn't see this until I plotted out the 1, 2, 3, 4, ... n month log differences in yields. There is an abrupt change in volatility starting in the 1950s that has increased over time, especially in the last 15 years to the present. When I first analyzed the data, I included data from 1900 on, which had a modest and relatively constant volatility regime. That skewed my results and probability estimates much lower. Lesson - ALWAYS check the plots for changes in character, etc that may not be observed in aggregate distributions. In addition, @JamesEE makes a very good point that this question is positive if the yield just touches the threshold one time. Given this, I'm updating my probability today quite a bit.
I would need to simulate the volatility better but it's a good point that it just needs to touch 2.25.

It only has to close at or above 2.25% on one day to meet the criterion. And, as others have pointed out, 7.5% inflation has the market expecting a half point increase in short-term interest rates in March. I'll increase the odds to 67%.

Using monthly 10 year yields since 1900, I used Tom Keelin's 4-factor metalog distribution to model the dispersion over time. It turns out be a very highly peaked central moment with widely dispersed tails (ie, extremely not-normal) over the short time period posed in the question. This implies ~7% chance of exceeding the 2.25% boundary. After averaging with the crowd estimate, I come up with 26% for the chance. Will adjust as needed as more data becomes available

So lack of action on multiple occasions over the next 6-12 months will actually be more impactful that it would have been had they not indicated a high level of hawkishness.

Few factors at play here: 1) When was the last time the US10Y was above 2.25%? Looks like May/June 2019 -- so pre-COVID. And it looks like yields few substantially heading into 2020. So in order for yields to return/exceed that level we'd like the US economy to return to pre-COVID levels, substantial re-rating of inflation expectations, or a material change in the supply/demand dynamic of the bond market. 2) So let's consider how the Fed is looking at the economy / their monetary policy -- Jay Powells "hawkish pivot" certainly increased the likelihood of higher rates/accelerated tapering to combat inflation (https://www.ft.com/content/bbbd46e1-75b3-4882-a2c8-bde7a8df7620). 3) So with a quicker taper (less demand for bonds from the Fed, means bond prices down, yields up). 4) On the jobs front the picture seems mixed (https://www.reuters.com/business/us-job-openings-jump-11-million-october-2021-12-08/) but generally seems like we are trending in the right direction and could approach pre-pandemic levels by the summer 5) Given the above picture, I think there is a likelihood that the US10Y could approach pre-pandemic levels by July 1, but pre-pandemic it appears the yields were <2% -- seemed to trade around 1.90% pretty well. 6) There is also a debt angle at play here -- be it a global "taper tantrum" issue or the levels of domestic debt in the US which has risen substantially (total debt >350%) which may limit the level rates can rise given this debt trap and negative consequences of forced develeraging.

The key points which influence the 10 year US yield 1> The real rate of growth - The rate which one would expect to earn if there were no inflation. (In other words if inflation were accounted for). This can be ascertained from the long term expectations of growth or the TIPS (which is an indicator of the inflation adjusted return) As of now, the 10 year US TIPS is negative, which means longer term growth prospects are poor. https://www.cnbc.com/quotes/US10YTIP Which means that the market thinks the current prospects for long term growth are dim. 2> Inflation - The US 10 year yield = The TIPS rate + Expected inflation. This equation gives a rough sense of what the market expects the average inflation to be over the next 10 years. Based on the closing prices of 10th Dec 21, this is approx 2.5% {i.e 1.49% - (-1.009%)} 3> Credit risk - If credit risk in the economy rises, demand for US government debt will rise leading to a fall in the yields as US government debt is considered the safest of all borrowings. So to sum up If Inflation rises (ie market thinks average inflation over 10 years is going to be higher than 2.5%). The US 10Y yield will go up. If long term growth prospects improve then the US 10Y yield will go up and vice versa. If credit risk in the economy increases the Yield will go down as people will prefer to hold US government securities instead of corporate loans(The TED spread is a decent measure of credit risk )https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/TEDRATE
